00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:52.710
[APPLAUSE]

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:59.310
You must become part of that
industry, whatever it takes.

00:42:59.310 --> 00:43:03.520
If it means waging
battle, time for battle.

00:43:03.520 --> 00:43:05.970
Because otherwise, it's
going to slow down.

00:43:05.970 --> 00:43:13.630
And why slow down technology
when all could enjoy it?

00:43:13.630 --> 00:43:15.240
Why slow down knowledge?

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:16.210
It should be those.

00:43:16.210 --> 00:43:19.680
So I think we should all
sort of huddle together.

00:43:19.680 --> 00:43:23.530
The game has begun already.

00:43:23.530 --> 00:43:29.820
The ardent fans cheering
for the game to go.

00:43:29.820 --> 00:43:32.490
They don't care about
winners and losers.

00:43:32.490 --> 00:43:34.730
They enjoy the spectacle.

00:43:34.730 --> 00:43:36.510
So we must give it to them.

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:39.960
And the spectacle
will be when we fully

00:43:39.960 --> 00:43:45.230
understand that cinema, or
any entertainment medium,

00:43:45.230 --> 00:43:47.115
is about the content
and the performance.

00:43:47.115 --> 00:43:51.460
And above all, the enjoyment
of the larger majority.

00:43:51.460 --> 00:43:56.030
Not the enjoyment of a few
who are playing on the stage.

00:43:56.030 --> 00:44:00.070
They both enjoy equally,
but this enjoyment

00:44:00.070 --> 00:44:02.390
comes from there.

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:06.270
They cannot perform on their
own and feel the same happiness.

00:44:06.270 --> 00:44:10.210
So it's time that we
get together and connect

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:12.060
that last mile.

00:44:12.060 --> 00:44:16.380
And that last mile might be
uphill, might be bloody battle,

00:44:16.380 --> 00:44:17.730
but it has to be done.

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:21.113
And I'm not going to
die on the battlefield.

00:44:21.113 --> 00:44:23.040
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:23.040 --> 00:44:25.520
I won't run away
from it, either.

00:44:25.520 --> 00:44:28.020
APARNA CHENNAPRAGADA: So the
next question from the audience

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:31.570
was, if you were to make
a Hollywood movie today,

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:32.900
what would it be about?

00:44:32.900 --> 00:44:34.525
KAMAL HAASAN: Oh,
they already made it.

00:44:34.525 --> 00:44:37.024
Whenever I think of
something, they make it.

00:44:37.024 --> 00:44:38.804
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:40.750 --> 00:44:43.250
APARNA CHENNAPRAGADA: And
who would your four stars be?

00:44:43.250 --> 00:44:46.550
KAMAL HAASAN: There are so
many talented people here.

00:44:46.550 --> 00:44:49.500
It makes me want to cry.

00:44:49.500 --> 00:44:52.170
That's how many talented
people there are.

00:44:52.170 --> 00:44:54.700
Some names I don't even know.

00:44:54.700 --> 00:44:56.480
But look at Ryan Gosling.

00:44:56.480 --> 00:44:58.480
Look at Tom Hardy.

00:44:58.480 --> 00:45:03.450
Tom Hardy is somebody who I
could either applaud or kill.

00:45:03.450 --> 00:45:06.170
I'll only do two
things for the man.

00:45:06.170 --> 00:45:10.480
But he'll have to keep
that performance going.

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:16.129
He's doing what Brando and
all did with tremendous pace.

00:45:16.129 --> 00:45:16.670
I don't know.

00:45:16.670 --> 00:45:18.870
What would I do?

00:45:18.870 --> 00:45:22.555
He's every actor's envy.

00:45:22.555 --> 00:45:24.510
And there's a way to go.

00:45:24.510 --> 00:45:27.660
And there are so many people.

00:45:27.660 --> 00:45:29.080
And so many things to do.

00:45:29.080 --> 00:45:34.350
And "Revenant" is
a film I always

00:45:34.350 --> 00:45:36.900
wanted to make because
it was already made

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:38.530
as "Lost in the Wilderness."

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:43.310
It's from a lore.

00:45:43.310 --> 00:45:45.350
It's a true story, but
it has happened before.

00:45:45.350 --> 00:45:49.080
When I saw that film, one
day, I will make that film.

00:45:49.080 --> 00:45:53.750
And Alejandro beat it to me.

00:45:53.750 --> 00:45:54.250
He did.

00:45:54.250 --> 00:45:56.390
It's a fantastic film.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:46:00.350
But it gives me
more energy anger,

00:46:00.350 --> 00:46:05.520
because I can feel the
breath of man behind me.

00:46:05.520 --> 00:46:08.570
And I can see the kicking of
the dust of the man running

00:46:08.570 --> 00:46:10.340
in front of me, is coming.

00:46:10.340 --> 00:46:14.260
I can taste the earth
that's coming from his foot.

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:15.920
And the lion is there.

00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:17.450
We can see.

00:46:17.450 --> 00:46:18.270
But it's fun.

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:20.590
I enjoy it.

00:46:20.590 --> 00:46:22.270
I am in this.

00:46:22.270 --> 00:46:24.940
They ask me, what
are you working on?

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:27.830
And how do you manage?

00:46:27.830 --> 00:46:30.220
Everybody asks me
these questions.

00:46:30.220 --> 00:46:32.550
I give a very
disappointing answer.

00:46:32.550 --> 00:46:35.620
I don't work anymore.

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:41.120
It's about 20, 25 years
since I stopped working.

00:46:41.120 --> 00:46:42.160
I still get paid.

00:46:42.160 --> 00:46:43.410
I still make movies.

00:46:43.410 --> 00:46:45.420
I love it.

00:46:45.420 --> 00:46:45.920
So--

00:46:45.920 --> 00:46:47.530
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:47.530 --> 00:46:51.860
I don't consider
that as work at all.

00:46:51.860 --> 00:46:55.310
I'm so grateful for
whatever money they give me.

00:46:55.310 --> 00:46:56.280
I'm so happy.

00:46:56.280 --> 00:47:00.924
Because nobody pays
you for your holiday.

00:47:00.924 --> 00:47:03.340
APARNA CHENNAPRAGADA: You've
done a variety of genre films

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:04.714
in different parts
of filmmaking.

00:47:04.714 --> 00:47:06.280
Is there a new genre?

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:08.600
Is there something new
that's on your mind

00:47:08.600 --> 00:47:10.270
recently that you
want to explore?

00:47:10.270 --> 00:47:11.686
KAMAL HAASAN: Oh,
there's so many.

00:47:11.686 --> 00:47:13.020
It's going to happen.

00:47:13.020 --> 00:47:15.380
As a matter of fact,
for [INAUDIBLE],

00:47:15.380 --> 00:47:17.830
Jean-Claude Carriere
and I had a thought,

00:47:17.830 --> 00:47:22.260
because we wanted to shoot
it with multiple cameras.

00:47:22.260 --> 00:47:30.060
Of course, it's a nightmare
for every producer when

00:47:30.060 --> 00:47:32.970
the director says, I
want multiple cameras.

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:36.180
That means cost will go up.

00:47:36.180 --> 00:47:41.260
A take, to become perfect,
will take so many takes.

00:47:41.260 --> 00:47:43.940
So but what we
wanted to do is work

00:47:43.940 --> 00:47:48.920
with three primary
cameras-- and many more.

00:47:48.920 --> 00:47:52.490
But three primary cameras
where the French film will have

00:47:52.490 --> 00:47:56.590
a different cut, perspective.

00:47:56.590 --> 00:48:01.350
English and Tamil in one film.

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:06.450
We'll send it to those areas
with those point of views.

00:48:06.450 --> 00:48:11.430
Like, when we want to see
this film of us talking,

00:48:11.430 --> 00:48:14.620
where would you want
the camera to be?

00:48:14.620 --> 00:48:15.973
Here.

00:48:15.973 --> 00:48:18.230
Not there.

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:22.570
So our, probably here and here.

00:48:22.570 --> 00:48:24.240
That's what pleases us.

00:48:24.240 --> 00:48:27.330
So the script was
written that way.

00:48:27.330 --> 00:48:31.130
We didn't even share it with
anyone because if we had,

00:48:31.130 --> 00:48:35.650
that would have been another
reason to stop the film.

00:48:35.650 --> 00:48:37.950
So there are so many
things that you could do,

00:48:37.950 --> 00:48:39.980
innovative things.

00:48:39.980 --> 00:48:42.640
Now you have so
many things coming.

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:48.930
You can make the audience
look around and still

00:48:48.930 --> 00:48:51.080
have content everywhere.

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:52.980
And this is nothing new for me.

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:57.070
When I was about
five-year or six-year-old,

00:48:57.070 --> 00:49:01.700
there was a exhibition
called Circorama which

00:49:01.700 --> 00:49:04.250
came to my town, [? Cheni ?].

00:49:04.250 --> 00:49:08.350
It was a big tent they
built. The audience

00:49:08.350 --> 00:49:13.010
were herded inside
a huge circus tent.

00:49:13.010 --> 00:49:17.420
And all the projection
rooms were outside.

00:49:17.420 --> 00:49:25.480
And I saw a speech by Abraham
Lincoln, Gettysburg speech

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:26.190
or something.

00:49:26.190 --> 00:49:28.720
I didn't know much English then.

00:49:28.720 --> 00:49:30.615
Something was
happening in English.

00:49:30.615 --> 00:49:34.120
And you had this
Lincoln Memorial thing.

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:36.970
And we were in the middle.

00:49:36.970 --> 00:49:37.810
It was astounding.

00:49:37.810 --> 00:49:41.440
You have to stand and watch.

00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:45.356
So when they say 360
degree camera now,

00:49:45.356 --> 00:49:48.500
I say, I've seen it.

00:49:48.500 --> 00:49:49.430
So that is technology.

00:49:49.430 --> 00:49:53.330
That's how delayed technology
becomes, sometimes,

00:49:53.330 --> 00:49:55.540
for good reasons
and bad reasons.

00:49:55.540 --> 00:49:57.415
APARNA CHENNAPRAGADA:
It's a related question

00:49:57.415 --> 00:50:00.520
to what you just said,
which is, what role do you

00:50:00.520 --> 00:50:03.030
think personally you want
to play in the pushing

00:50:03.030 --> 00:50:08.490
this technology
towards the frontier?

00:50:08.490 --> 00:50:11.180
You've always been, as you
said, like the bleeding edge.

00:50:11.180 --> 00:50:13.150
KAMAL HAASAN: Simply
get in there and do it.

00:50:13.150 --> 00:50:16.270
Don't keep deliberating
and talking about it.

00:50:16.270 --> 00:50:18.580
What's the worst
thing that can happen?

00:50:18.580 --> 00:50:19.880
Is you'll fail.

00:50:19.880 --> 00:50:22.162
That's data for future work.

00:50:22.162 --> 00:50:24.070
[APPLAUSE]

